      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Read and understand the entire owner&rsquo;s manual before attempting assembly or operation.</strong> Do not use this tool until proper training and knowledge has been obtained.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Keep guards in place and in working order.</li>
        <li>Keep fingers and hands away from the spindle while in operation. Avoid getting fingers too close to the drum.</li>
        <li>Remove adjusting keys and wrenches before operating.</li>
        <li>Keep work area clean. Cluttered areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not use in damp or wet locations or expose to rain.</li>
        <li>Keep children and visitors a safe distance from the work area.</li>
        <li>Do not force the tool. It will do the job better and safer at its designed rate.</li>
        <li>Wear proper apparel. No loose clothing, gloves, neckties, rings, bracelets, or other jewelry. Wear nonslip footwear and protective hair covering.</li>
        <li>Always wear safety glasses compliant with ANSI Z87.1. Use a face or dust mask if the operation is dusty.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach. Keep proper footing and balance at all times.</li>
        <li>Turn the machine off and unplug before changing spindles.</li>
        <li>Make sure the spindle drum is in good condition with no tears or holes before operating.</li>
        <li>Disconnect before servicing or changing accessories.</li>
        <li>Make sure the switch is in the OFF position before plugging in the power cord.</li>
        <li>Never stand on the tool.</li>
        <li>Check damaged parts before further use to ensure proper operation and alignment.</li>
        <li>Do not operate under the influence of drugs, alcohol, or medication.</li>
        <li>Never leave the tool running while unattended. Turn off and wait for a complete stop.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Unpacking &amp; Setup</h2>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove all contents from the shipping container. Do not discard any shipping material until the sander is set up and running properly.</li>
        <li>Report any damage to your local distributor and/or shipping company.</li>
        <li>Clean all rust-protected surfaces with a mild solvent or kerosene. Do not use lacquer thinner, paint thinner, or gasoline as these will damage painted surfaces.</li>
        <li>Apply a light coating of sealer to the table surface to prevent rust.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Spindle &amp; Insert Holders</h2>

      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p05_00.jpg" alt="Fig 1 &ndash; Spindle and insert holder installation" />
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p05_01.jpg" alt="Fig 2 &ndash; Installing spindle into housing" />
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Attach the spindle holder (A, Fig. 1) and the insert holder (B, Fig. 1) to the cabinet using six hex socket cap screws.</li>
        <li>Clean the inserts and spindles. Place them in the appropriate holder.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Installing Spindles</h2>

      <ol>
        <li>Before inserting the threaded spindle into the spindle housing, make sure the surfaces are clean.</li>
        <li>Thread the spindle <strong>counter-clockwise</strong> into the spindle housing.</li>
        <li>Using the provided wrenches, tighten the spindle nut (A, Fig. 2) <strong>counter-clockwise</strong> while holding the spindle housing flat (B, Fig. 2) with the other wrench.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        Do not overtighten the spindle as it may be difficult to remove after the sanding operation.
      </div>

      <h2>Insert Plates</h2>

      <p>Always use an insert plate. There are 2 oblong and 2 round insert plates included. The oblong insert plates are used when the table is tilted for bevel sanding. Each plate has a notch on the outer edge to ensure proper insertion.</p>

      <h2>Setup for 90&deg;</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p06_00.jpg" alt="Fig 3 &ndash; Setup for 90-degree sanding" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 3 &ndash; 90&deg; setup with table adjustment knobs, square, pointer, and stop</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Loosen both knobs (A, Fig. 3) and place the table in the 0&deg; position.</li>
        <li>Place a square (B, Fig. 3) on the table. Rest the long section against the sanding drum. The square should be flat against both the table and the sanding drum.</li>
        <li>If adjustment is needed, loosen both knobs and tilt the table so the square is flat against table and drum.</li>
        <li>Make sure the pointer (C, Fig. 3) reads 0&deg;. If adjustment is needed, loosen the screw (D, Fig. 3) and adjust to the correct position.</li>
        <li>Adjust the 90&deg; stop (E, Fig. 3) with a hex wrench so that it rests against the bottom side of the table.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Setup for Bevel Sanding</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p06_01.jpg" alt="Fig 4 &ndash; Bevel sanding setup and dust port" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 4 &ndash; Bevel sanding adjustment and dust port location</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Loosen both knobs (A, Fig. 4) and adjust the table to the desired angle.</li>
        <li>Tighten both knobs.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Dust Collection</h2>

      <p>The dust port (B, Fig. 4) can be connected directly to a 2&quot; hose for dust collection.</p>

      <h2>Turning the Sander On &amp; Off</h2>

      <div class="note">
        Before connecting the sander to the power source, make sure the switch is in the OFF position.
      </div>

      <p>Flip the switch to the ON position to start the sander. There is a removable safety key in the tip of the switch that can be removed in the OFF position. When the key is removed, the sander cannot be started.</p>

      <h2>Removing Spindles</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p07_00.jpg" alt="Fig 5 &ndash; Removing spindles" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 5 &ndash; Loosening the spindle nut for removal</figcaption>
      </div>

      <p>Using the provided wrenches, loosen the spindle nut (A, Fig. 5) <strong>clockwise</strong> while holding the spindle housing flat (B, Fig. 5) with the other wrench.</p>

      <h2>Changing Sanding Sleeves</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/jet-jbos-5/p07_01.jpg" alt="Fig 6 &ndash; Changing sanding sleeves" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 6 &ndash; Sanding sleeve clamp and nut details</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>1/4&quot;, 1/2&quot;, and 5/8&quot; Spindles</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the clamp (A, Fig. 6) with a cross-point screwdriver.</li>
        <li>Remove the sanding sleeve from the spindle shaft.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>1-1/2&quot; and 2&quot; Spindles (optional 3&quot;)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the nut (B, Fig. 6) with the provided wrench.</li>
        <li>Remove the sanding sleeve from the spindle shaft.</li>
        <li>Reverse these steps to install new sanding sleeves.</li>
      </ol>

